    The Department of Geography Sustainability Urban and Community Studies at UConn is hiring a fully-funded MA/PhD student with an interest in GIS and Community Studies to begin in Fall 2024.
    Carol Atkinson-PalomboCarol Atkinson-Palombo 3rd+ 3rd+ Geography Professor Specializing in Sustainable Cities; Sustainable Transportation; Social Dimensions of Renewable EnergyGeography Professor Specializing in Sustainable Cities; Sustainable Transportation; Social Dimensions of Renewable Energy 3d 3 days ago
    The Department of Geography Sustainability Urban and Community Studies at UConn is hiring a fully-funded MA/PhD student with an interest in GIS and Community Studies to begin in Fall 2024. We seek a student with a strong interest and passion for learning and applying GIS skills and in particular Web GIS, spatial database management, and visualization, to community-based research projects. This two-year project is a collaboration with UConns Research on Resilient Cities, Racism, and Equity (RRCRE) initiative, and will involve hands-on experience in building a GIS database and web applications to explore neighborhood change in the Greater Hartford Area to improve the well-being of residents. There is tremendous potential for the student to develop a unique thesis/dissertation topic that builds upon this project. Student funding will be a combination of research assistantships (RA) and teaching assistantships (TA) for up to 4 years in the case of a PhD student, subject to satisfactory performance. UConn offers a competitive funding package for graduate students (e.g., the 9- month Level-2 stipend for academic year 2024-2025 is $29,214 and includes a tuition waiver). Required Qualifications Experience with GIS mapping and data visualization Experience and skills in spatial database management Strong communication skills (in written and spoken English) Passion for urban and community studies Preferred Qualifications Prior experience with ESRIs web application products (e.g. Story Maps, Dashboards, Experience Builder) Prior experience with open GIS, web development, and web hosting (e.g, QGIS, JavaScript, HTML/CSS, GitHub, Mapbox) Previous experience with community-engaged research projects. If interested, contact Professor Peter Chen (peter.chen@uconn.edu) and Professor Carol Atkinson-Palombo (carol.atkinson-palombo@uconn.edu) with your CV by June 25th. To learn more about our department, visit our website (https://lnkd.in/eGsamKdg). For detailed information on how to apply go to our admissions page.
    Home | Department of Geography
    geography.uconn.edu

    Good news! Prof. Matthew Kasemer of the The University of Alabama Graduate School United States is currently searching for a PhD student. This fully-funded position is in support of a project focused on how irradiation affects the mechanical behavior or materials. The student will implement models considering effects due to irradiation into a crystal plasticity finite element framework, and model the deformation response of samples informed by experimental post-irradiation examination. This project will offer a unique opportunity to collaborate with scientists at multiple national laboratories, and even visit the Advanced Photon Source to support high energy diffraction microscopy experiments. Qualified candidates should have significant experience with programming and a background in the mechanical behavior of materials (i.e., mechanical engineering, metallurgical engineering, materials science, or other relevant fields).   • Feed post

    Your Grad CoachYour Grad Coach 3rd+ 3rd+ Your go-to for brilliant SOPs, scholarship tips, outstanding CVs, interview prep & much more- chat now!Your go-to for brilliant SOPs, scholarship tips, outstanding CVs, interview prep & much more- chat now! 13h 13 hours ago
    How to Study as a Fully Funded PhD Student in Finland 1. Research Finnish Universities & PhD Programs Top Universities: University of Helsinki, Aalto University, University of Turku, University of Eastern Finland, and Tampere University. Program Finder: Use Studyinfo.fi to search for PhD programs and understand entry requirements. Research Institutes: Explore opportunities at institutes like VTT Technical Research Centre of Finland and Finnish Environment Institute (SYKE). 2. Identify Funding Opportunities Doctoral Schools: Many Finnish universities have specific doctoral schools offering funding. Check out Helsinki Universitys Doctoral Schools and Aalto Universitys Doctoral Programs. Government Scholarships: Apply for the Finnish Government Scholarship Pool for non-EU/EEA students. Foundations and Grants: Look for grants from CIMO and Kone Foundation. 3. Craft a Strong Research Proposal Align with National Interests: Focus on areas like sustainable technology, education, and Arctic research, which are key research areas in Finland. Collaborative Projects: Emphasize potential collaboration with Finnish industries or EU research projects. 4. Preparing Application Documents Personal Statement: Tailor your statement to reflect your interest in Finnish research priorities and the specific program. CV: Include relevant research experience, publications, and any prior collaborations with Finnish institutions. Letters of Recommendation: Secure letters from professors or industry professionals familiar with your research capabilities. 5. Contact Potential Supervisors Email Strategy: Craft a concise and focused email. Highlight your research interests, how they align with the professors work, and your funding plans. Finding Supervisors: Use university websites and platforms like Academia.edu and ResearchGate to identify and connect with potential supervisors. 6. Submit Your Application Application Portals: Submit your application through university-specific portals. For example, University of Helsinkis Application Portal. Deadlines: Adhere to specific program deadlines, which can vary. Typically, applications are due in January or February for autumn intake. 7. Prepare for the Interview Interview Prep: Be ready to discuss your research proposal in detail, your motivation for choosing Finland, and your understanding of the programs structure. Mock Interviews: Conduct mock interviews with peers or mentors to practice your responses. Useful Resources Study in Finland: Study in Finland Portal Doctoral Training in Finland: University of Helsinki Guide Research.fi: Finnish Research Portal Finnish Foundations and Scholarships: Grant Finder DM me if you need help securing a fully funded PhD in Finland! hashtag#PhD hashtag#Finland hashtag#Research hashtag#HigherEducation hashtag#StudyAbroad hashtag#FullyFunded hashtag#DoctoralStudies

    Surabhi JainSurabhi Jain 3rd+ 3rd+ Founder | Social Impact Leader | Thought Partner | Network Weaver | Systems Thinker | CoachFounder | Social Impact Leader | Thought Partner | Network Weaver | Systems Thinker | Coach 17h Edited 17 hours ago
    About two years ago, I started a journey to learn as much as I could about power and privilege so I could apply it to my work. As I have shared before, I grew up with a negative connotation of power. I didn't think it could mean anything positive, much less be used in a positive manner. Two years on, I have a very different relationship with power. I have not only learned the different meanings of power and the different types of power but come to realize that I was exercising power positively way before I knew that I was doing that. Two years ago, I gave myself the best gift I could when I turned 40 - the gift of lifelong learning and the quest to become a better self. The many wise women in my life, especially Clair Minson, who told me to study these topics on my own and create a self-funded fellowship of sorts instead of going to school, I thank you for your wisdom. I feel like I am on a path to a self-created PhD program where I get to pick and choose what I am learning and deepen my practice in that area for 4-6 months and then move on to the next topic. This self-funded fellowship/PhD program has given birth to Women In Power. It has given rise to multiple communities of practice that I designed and co-lead/co-facilitate. It has helped me take a deeper look at my relationship with topics of diversity, equity, belonging, inclusion, respect, justice, etc. I have a much healthier relationship, I can speak more intelligently, and I am far more aware of these issues than I was two years ago. So, as I continue on this journey for the next 2 years or maybe 4, I hope I will continue to apply my learnings to be a better leader and a better human being. Here's to learning that leads to self-development and growth! hashtag#leadership hashtag#growth hashtag#learning hashtag#womeninpower hashtag#powerXprivilege hashtag#fellowship hashtag#phd
